"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody, today I'm going to pitch my compost pile for the very first time. I set it up just about three, four days ago. And the first pitching is really about mixing it and trying to get it as evenly distributed as you can between the carbon and the nitrogen. The first day is really all about just setting it up. And so it's real easy. The second day is a little bit more not difficult, but I'd say there's more involved with it because I'm trying to get a good mix on. I'm evaluating the moisture as I go along. We've received a ton of rain since I put this thing together, so I don't need to add any more moisture. Normally I would, and there's a couple branches that I put in there that I thought would break down because they were real thin and they haven't. As I go along, of course, I'm trying to keep as tidy as I can by uh raking as much as I can. And then I'll go back to the pitching. And as you see, I get caught a couple of places where these branches are getting the way, so I just take them out as I'm going. And that's part of doing this uh first pitching, is you're making the pile as evenly and as consistent, and there's a little bit of steam as can, but really there's not a whole lot of heat going because it hasn't been mixed properly, and that's what this first pitching is about. Now, as I do this first pitching, I'm going to have to cover it uh with what's called a carbon cap because there's a going to be a lot of rotten vegetable refuse and hay filled with manure and all this on the outside. And here I'll give you a quick showing of that. See all that debris, all that uh vegetable refuse? That has to get covered up because it's gonna smell, and also I'm gonna lose the valuable nitrogen that that stuff is gonna let off, and that's why it smells. And nitrogen is what's smelling. It's collecting little bits of vegetable refuse with it and escaping. So I'm going to basically go over to my uh wood chip pile and just start shoveling over a bunch of wood chips to cover this uh pile up. And this is what's called a carbon cap. Basically taking the high carbon substance like leaves or wood chips and covering the pile after you've pitched it. And I'll probably do this for one or two times until the pile is well distributed and well broken up and very even. So this is the stage where I'm actually kind of adding more carbon with each pitching just to cover it up, but also because as the nitrogen uh rich materials react to the carbon, you're you're gonna find it you need to add more carbon, generally speaking. And uh this is what it looks like when it's all finished up. Nice, even not and there's no garbage on top, doesn't smell gonna be a great pile, looking forward to it. Probably gonna add some water next time, but didn't need to this time. And uh anyway, thanks y'all. Appreciate you watching.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody, today I'm going to pitch my compost pile for the very first time.\",\n      \"start\": 0.24,\n      \"end\": 5.04,\n      \"duration\": 4.8,\n      \"confidence\": 0.995,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 0.24,\n          \"end\": 0.48,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 0.996\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 0.48,\n          \"end\": 0.56,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 0.64,\n          \"end\": 0.8,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 0.8,\n          \"end\": 0.96,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 0.96,\n          \"end\": 1.04,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \",\